This factorized form implies further restrictions on the 
coefficients of the four-point amplitude (\ref{Ampl}). Indeed, expanding the product of the prefactor $R^{2222}$ with the function $F^{(2)}$ and matching the 
propagator structures arising with those in eq. (\ref{Ampl}), we can  
express  the original coefficients $a,b,c,d$ in terms of 
$\alpha_p$ and $\beta_p$. The coefficients $a_p$ are given by  
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{a}
a_1(s,t)=s\alpha_1(s,t)\, ,~~~~~a_2(s,t)=\alpha_2(s,t)\, , ~~~~~a_3(s,t)=t\alpha_3(s,t) \, .
\end{eqnarray}
For the coefficients $b_p$ we obtain 
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
b_1&=&s\beta_3+\alpha_1(t-s-1)\, ,  ~~~~~~~~~b_4=\beta_3+\alpha_2(t-s-1)\, , \\
\label{b}
b_2&=&s\beta_2+\alpha_1(1-s-t)\, ,  ~~~~~~~~~b_5=t\beta_2+\alpha_3(1-s-t) \, ,\\
\nonumber
b_3&=&\beta_1+\alpha_2(s-t-1) \, ,  ~~~~~~~~~~b_6=t\beta_1+\alpha_3(s-t-1)  \, .
\end{eqnarray}
For $c_p$ we have
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
c_1&=&\alpha_1+s\alpha_2+(t-s-1)\beta_3 \, ,\\
\label{c}
c_2&=&t\alpha_1+s\alpha_3+(1-s-t)\beta_2 \, ,\\
\nonumber
c_3&=&\alpha_3+t\alpha_2+(s-t-1)\beta_1 \, .
\end{eqnarray}
Finally, the coefficients $d_p$ read  
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
d_1&=&\alpha_1(s-t-1)+s\beta_1+\beta_2(t-s-1)+\beta_3(1-t-s) \, ,\\
\label{d}
d_2&=&\alpha_2(1-s-t)+\beta_2+\beta_1(t-s-1)+\beta_3(s-t-1) \, ,\\
\nonumber
d_3&=&\alpha_3(t-s-1)+t\beta_3+\beta_1(1-s-t)+\beta_2(s-t-1) \, . 
\end{eqnarray}

Now, under point permutations the prefactor $R^{2222}$ transforms as follows 
\begin{eqnarray}
1\leftrightarrow 2: && R^{2222} \ \rightarrow \ \frac{1}{t}\; R^{2222} \nonumber\\
1\leftrightarrow 3: && R^{2222} \ \rightarrow \  R^{2222}\;  \label{crossR}
\end{eqnarray}
(the harmonic factors are symmetric, e.g. $(12)=(21)$).
This implies that crossing symmetry relates the three coefficients $\alpha_p$ as follows: \begin{eqnarray} \label{cross1}
\alpha_1(s,t)=\alpha_3(t,s)=1/s~\alpha_2(t/s,1/s)=1/t~\alpha_1(s/t,1/t) \, ,
\end{eqnarray}
while for the $\beta$'s we obtain 
\begin{eqnarray}   \label{cross2}
\beta_3(s,t)=\beta_1(t,s)=1/t~\beta_2(s/t,1/t)=1/s~\beta_3(1/s,t/s)\, .
\end{eqnarray}
Thus, the insertion formula reduces the number of independent functions from four to two. This is the content of the partial renormalization theorem for ${\textstyle \frac{1}{2}}$-BPS operators of weight 4. We identify these two independent functions with, e.g., ${\cal F}\equiv \alpha_1$ and ${\cal G}\equiv \beta_3$, satisfying a single crossing symmetry 
condition each:
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{cr}
{\cal F}(s,t)=1/t~{\cal F}(s/t,1/t) \, , ~~~~~{\cal G}(s,t)=1/s~{\cal G}(1/s,t/s)\, .
\end{eqnarray} 
In Section \ref{oneloopamp} we compute these functions in perturbation theory at one loop, and in Section \ref{gravity} in the supergravity approximation, thus confirming the partial non-renormalization theorem.

We conclude this section by presenting the free-field theory values of the  coefficient functions in the large $N$ limit:
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{free}
a_{1,2,3}=1\, , ~~~~~~b_{1,\cdots,6}=\frac{16}{N^2}\, , ~~~~~~c_{1,2,3}=\frac{16}{N^2}\, , ~~~~~~
d_{1,2,3}=\frac{32}{N^2} \, .
\end{eqnarray}  

