\section{$D$-functions.}\label{B}
Here we present the coefficient functions of the four-point amplitude for the ${\textstyle \frac{1}{2}}$-BPS
operators of weight 4 and outline the basic steps of how they can be further 
simplified. 

The original four-point amplitude obtained by summing up different AdS graphs is written in terms 
of the so-called $D$-functions.
The $D$-functions related to $AdS_{d+1}$ are defined by the formula \cite{DHFMMR}
\begin{eqnarray} 
\label{defD} \hskip -0.2cm
D_{\Delta_1\Delta_2\Delta_3\Delta_4}(x_1,x_2,x_3,x_4)= \int \frac{{\rm d}^{d} 
w~ {\rm d} w_0}{w_0^{d+1}} \prod_{i=1}^4 K_{\Delta_i}(x) \, , \quad K_{\Delta}(x)
= \left(\frac{w_0}{w_0^2+(\vec{w}-x)^2}\right)^{\Delta} \!  ,
\end{eqnarray} 
where the integral is taken over the space parametrized by $w=(w_0,\vec{w})$, 
$\vec{w}$ being a $d$-dimensional vector.
In what follows it is useful to introduce 
the $\overline D$-functions \cite{DO} which depend on the conformal cross-ratios $s$ and $t$
and are related to the corresponding $D$-functions as follows:
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
 \bar{D}_{\Delta_1\Delta_2\Delta_3\Delta_4}(s,t)=\frac{2\prod_i\Gamma(\Delta_i) }{\pi^{d/2}\Gamma(\Sigma-d/2)}
\frac{(x_{13}^2)^{\Sigma-\Delta_4}(x_{24}^2)^{\Delta_2}}{(x_{14}^2)^{\Sigma-\Delta_1-\Delta_4}(x_{34}^2)^{\Sigma-\Delta_3-\Delta_4} }
 D_{\Delta_1\Delta_2\Delta_3\Delta_4}(x_1,x_2,x_3,x_4),
\end{eqnarray}
where $\Sigma=1/2\sum_i\Delta_i$. For $d=4$ and $\Delta_i=1$ we define $\overline D_{1111}=\Phi(s,t)$, where $\Phi(s,t)$ is the standard (one-loop) box integral in four dimensions.

In terms of the $\overline D$-functions the coefficient functions of the four-point amplitude for the ${\textstyle \frac{1}{2}}$-BPS operators of weight 4 read as follows:
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
a_1&=&-\frac{2}{N^2}s^2\Big[4\overline D_{2211}+4\overline D_{2222}+4(s-t-1)\overline D_{3322}
+2(s-2t-2)\overline D_{3333}\\
\nonumber
&+&s(s-4t-4)\overline D_{4433}-s(2+5s+2t)\overline D_{4444}+s^2(s-t-1)\overline D_{5544}
\Big] \, ;\\
\nonumber
b_1&=&\frac{4}{N^2}s^3\Big[9\overline D_{4343}+2\overline D_{4411}-10\overline D_{4422}-9\overline D_{4433}+3\overline D_{4435}+
12\overline D_{4444}+2t\overline D_{4521}\\
\nonumber
&+&(1-3s)\overline D_{4534}-2t\overline D_{4554}-2\overline D_{5421}-\overline D_{5434}+2(1-s+t)
(\overline D_{5533}+\overline D_{5544})  
\Big]\, ;
\end{eqnarray}
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
c_1&=&\frac{2}{N^2}\Big[16(\overline D_{3245}-\overline D_{3254}+s^2\overline D_{3425}-s^3\overline D_{3524})
+17s^2(\overline D_{4343}+\overline D_{4433})\\
\nonumber
&+&14s(\overline D_{4345}-\overline D_{4354}+s\overline D_{4435}-s^2\overline D_{4534})
+32s^2(\overline D_{4422}+\overline D_{4242})\\
\nonumber
&-&78s^2\overline D_{4444}
+s^2(s+t+15)\overline D_{5454}+s^2(1+15s+t)\overline D_{5544}
\Big] \, ;
\end{eqnarray}
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
d_1=\frac{4}{N^2}s^2\Big[81(\overline D_{4334}+t\overline D_{4343})
+9(t\overline D_{4435}+t\overline D_{4453}-st\overline D_{4534}-st\overline D_{4543}) \\
\nonumber
-6t(\overline D_{5454}+t\overline D_{4554})+64t\overline D_{4422}+30t\overline D_{4433}+2t(1-s+t)\overline D_{5544} 
\Big] \, .
\end{eqnarray}
These expressions are rather involved and to simplify them one has to use 
the various identities between $\overline D$'s. We refer the reader to Appendices 
D of Refs. \cite{DO,ADOS} where a complete list of the necessary identities is given 
and the basic technique of their usage is explained 
(see also the Appendix to Ref. \cite{DHFMMR}).  

We start by showing how the coefficient $a_1$ can be simplified.  To this end we 
need to successively use the following formulae:
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
(1-s+t)\overline D_{5544}&=&-2\overline D_{5535}+9\overline D_{4433}-7\overline D_{4444}\,  \\
\nonumber
(1-s+t)\overline D_{4444}&=&-2\overline D_{4435}+9\overline D_{3333}-6s\overline D_{4433} \, \\
\nonumber
s(1-s+t)\overline D_{4433}&=&-2\overline D_{3335}-5s\overline D_{3333}+4\overline D_{2233} \, \\
\nonumber
(1-s+t)\overline D_{3333}&=&-2\overline D_{3324}-4\overline D_{2233}+4\overline D_{2222}\, \\
\nonumber
(1-s+t)\overline D_{3322}&=&-2\overline D_{3313}+\overline D_{2211}-3\overline D_{2222} \, .
\end{eqnarray} 
After this we can make the further substitution 
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
s\overline D_{4435}&=&\overline D_{3346}-\overline D_{3335}\,  \\
\nonumber
s\overline D_{3324}&=&\overline D_{2235}-\overline D_{2224}\,  \\
\nonumber
s\overline D_{3335}&=&\overline D_{2246}-2\overline D_{2235}  
\end{eqnarray}
and $s\overline D_{3313}=\overline D_{2224}$, $s\overline D_{5535}=\overline D_{4446}$. In this way we obtain the formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
a_1=-\frac{4}{N^2}\Big(2s\overline D_{2246}+2s^2\overline D_{3346}+s^3\overline D_{4446}\Big) \, 
\end{eqnarray}
from which we read off the function ${\cal F}$ (\ref{simpleFG}).

Now we briefly describe the procedure for obtaining the second function ${\cal G}$
from the coefficient $b_1$. This time we need the following identities:
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
(t-s-1)\overline D_{6422}&=&2(\overline D_{5423}-\overline D_{5412}-2\overline D_{5322})+\frac{2}{s^3}\\
\nonumber
(t-s-1)\overline D_{6433}&=&\overline D_{5414}-3\overline D_{5423}+2\overline D_{5434}-4\overline D_{5333}\\
\nonumber
(t-s-1)\overline D_{6444}&=&2\overline D_{5445}-4(\overline D_{5434}+\overline D_{5344})+2\overline D_{5425}
\end{eqnarray}
which imply 
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{fp}
&&(t-s-1){\cal F}=\\
\nonumber
&&-\frac{8}{N^2}s^3\left(\overline D_{5445}-\overline D_{5423}+\overline D_{5425}+\overline D_{5414}-2\overline D_{5344}
-2\overline D_{5412}-4\overline D_{5333}-4\overline D_{5322}\right)-\frac{16}{N^2}
\end{eqnarray}
Substituting this into 
\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
{\cal G} \equiv \beta_3=\frac{1}{s}(b_1-(t-s-1){\cal F})
\end{eqnarray}
and making again use of the identities (D.7)-(D.11) from Ref. \cite{ADOS} we arrive at our final expression (\ref{simpleFG}).



